(1747–1836).   Gillies’s principal work was a history of Greece, but he  also translated two of Aristotle's works, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Nicomachean Ethics</title> and <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Politics</title>. 
 According to the <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title>, the ‘second edition of 1804 added a reply to criticism by the Platonist Thomas Taylor’.  Gillies’s earlier 
appearances tend to be at Paradise’s, and include this beguiling entry: Apr. 18. Su. Dine at Holcroft's : tea Paradise's, with sir R. A's Truchement , 
B. Hollis, Rutledge, Planta, Nollekens, Hawkins, Gillies, Russian chaplain, Cyclops. '</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The dates and the circles (Kippis, Planta, Hollis) do seem to match up - so that this identification can be considered probable.

